ce:section.ce:para:
We initially looked at pure AHEX in order to verify the reliability of our computational approach and to obtain pure AHEX data for comparison in the upcoming subsections. Fig. 1 depicts the fully optimized geometry of AHEX GQD. C–C bond lengths in the optimized AHEX structure ranged from 1.393 to 1.467 Å (Table 1
                        ). The lengths of carbon-carbon bonds were found to be equivalent to previously published theoretical values [84,85]. At the B3LYP/SDD level, the estimated HOMO-LUMO energy gap of AHEX was found to be 3.662 eV, which is in good agreement with the 3.668 eV value [86]. We then investigated the adsorption of NO, NO2, and NH3 on isolated AHEX. Fig. 1 (a-c) depicts the optimal structures for the gases under consideration. When the NO, NO2, and NH3 molecules are adsorbed on the isolated AHEX, the complex structures produced after comprehensive optimization are illustrated in (Fig. 2
                        a–c). In Table 1, the average distances between the three gases and the AHEX as well as the computed adsorption energies and charge transfers are listed. It was found that the binding distances of AHEX to NO, NO2, and NH3 molecules were 3.731 Å, 2.739 Å, and 3.443 Å, respectively. The results show that NO, NO2, and NH3 adsorptions on AHEX are extremely poor. For instance, the predicted adsorption energy of NO is 0.001 eV. Adsorption of NO2 and NH3 is similar (Eads = 0.024 eV, −0.061), and all pertain to physical adsorption. We anticipate that the AHEX- GQD will not be adequate for capturing or storing the three harmful gases due to its poor adsorption of NO, NO2, and NH3. We looked at the electronic state of (TM = Ni, Pd, and Pt) in a low-spin state in this work.
